# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: energy-harvesting-circuits
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Energy harvesters usually provide a very small amount of power for low-energy electronics.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] While the input fuel to some large-scale energy generation costs resources (oil, coal, etc.), the energy source for energy harvesters is present as ambient background.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] For example, temperature gradients exist from the operation of a combustion engine; in urban areas, there is a large amount of electromagnetic energy in the environment due to radio and television broadcasting.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] One of the first examples of ambient energy being used to produce electricity was the successful use of electromagnetic radiation (EMR) to generate the crystal radio.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The principles of energy harvesting from ambient EMR can be demonstrated with basic components.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Energy harvesting devices converting ambient energy into electrical energy have attracted much interest in both the military and commercial sectors.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Some systems convert motion, such as that of ocean waves, into electricity to be used by oceanographic monitoring sensors for autonomous operation.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Future applications may include high-power output devices (or arrays of such devices) deployed at remote locations to serve as reliable power stations for large systems.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Another application is in wearable electronics, where energy-harvesting devices can power or recharge cell phones, mobile computers, and radio communication equipment.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] All of these devices must be sufficiently robust to endure long-term exposure to hostile environments and have a broad range of dynamic sensitivity to exploit the entire spectrum of wave motions.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] In addition, one of the latest techniques to generate electric power from vibration waves is the utilization of Auxetic Boosters.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] This method falls under the category of piezoelectric-based vibration energy harvesting (PVEH), where the harvested electric energy can be directly used to power wireless sensors, monitoring cameras, and other Internet of Things (IoT) devices.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Energy can also be harvested to power small autonomous sensors such as those developed using MEMS technology.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] These systems are often very small and require little power, but their applications are limited by the reliance on battery power.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Scavenging energy from ambient vibrations, wind, heat, or light could enable smart sensors to function indefinitely.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Typical power densities available from energy harvesting devices are highly dependent upon the specific application (affecting the generator's size) and the design itself of the harvesting generator.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] In general, for motion-powered devices, typical values are a few μW/cm3 for human body-powered applications and hundreds of μW/cm3 for generators powered by machinery.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Most energy-scavenging devices for wearable electronics generate very little power.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] In general, energy can be stored in a capacitor, super capacitor, or battery.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Capacitors are used when the application needs to provide huge energy spikes.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Batteries leak less energy and are therefore used when the device needs to provide a steady flow of energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] These aspects of the battery depend on the type that is used.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] A common type of battery that is used for this purpose is the lead acid or lithium-ion battery although older types such as nickel metal hydride are still widely used today.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Compared to batteries, super capacitors have virtually unlimited charge-discharge cycles and can therefore operate forever, enabling a maintenance-free operation in IoT and wireless sensor devices.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Current interest in low-power energy harvesting is for independent sensor networks.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] In these applications, an energy harvesting scheme puts power stored into a capacitor then boosts/regulates it to a second storage capacitor or battery for use in the microprocessor or in the data transmission.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The power is usually used in a sensor application and the data is stored or transmitted, possibly through a wireless method.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] One of the main driving forces behind the search for new energy harvesting devices is the desire to power sensor networks and mobile devices without batteries that run on intermittent computing systems and need external charging or service.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Batteries have several limitations, such as limited lifespan, environmental impact, size, weight, and cost.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Energy harvesting devices can provide an alternative or complementary source of power for applications that require low power consumption, such as remote sensing, wearable electronics, condition monitoring, and wireless sensor networks.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Energy harvesting devices can also extend the battery life or enable batteryless operation of some applications.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Another motivation for energy harvesting is the potential to address the issue of climate change by reducing greenhouse gas emissions and fossil fuel consumption.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Energy harvesting devices can utilize renewable and clean sources of energy that are abundant and ubiquitous in the environment, such as solar, thermal, wind, and kinetic energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Energy harvesting devices can also reduce the need for power transmission and distribution systems that cause energy losses and environmental impacts.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Energy harvesting devices can therefore contribute to the development of a more sustainable and resilient energy system.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Recent research in energy harvesting has led to the innovation of devices capable of powering themselves through user interactions.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Notable examples include battery-free game boys and other toys, which showcase the potential of devices powered by the energy generated from user actions, such as pressing buttons or turning knobs.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] These studies highlight how energy harvested from interactions can not only power the devices themselves but also extend their operational autonomy, promoting the use of renewable energy sources and reducing reliance on traditional batteries.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] A possible source of energy comes from ubiquitous radio transmitters.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Historically, either a large collection area or close proximity to the radiating wireless energy source is needed to get useful power levels from this source.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The nantenna is one proposed development which would overcome this limitation by making use of the abundant natural radiation (such as solar radiation).
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] One idea is to deliberately broadcast RF energy to power and collect information from remote devices.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] This is now commonplace in passive radio-frequency identification (RFID) systems, but the Safety and US Federal Communications Commission (and equivalent bodies worldwide) limit the maximum power that can be transmitted this way to civilian use.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] This method has been used to power individual nodes in a wireless sensor network.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Various turbine and non-turbine generator technologies can harvest airflow.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Towered wind turbines and airborne wind energy systems (AWES) harness the flow of air.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Multiple companies are developing these technologies, which can operate in low-light environments, such as HVAC ducts, and can be scaled and optimized for the energy requirements of specific applications.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The flow of blood can also be utilized to power devices.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] For example, a pacemaker developed at the University of Bern, uses blood flow to wind up a spring, which then drives an electrical micro-generator.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Water energy harvesting has seen advancements in design, such as generators with transistor-like architecture, achieving high energy conversion efficiency and power density.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Photovoltaic (PV) energy harvesting wireless technology offers significant advantages over wired or solely battery-powered sensor solutions: virtually inexhaustible sources of power with little or no adverse environmental effects.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Indoor PV harvesting solutions have to date been powered by specially tuned amorphous silicon (aSi)a technology most used in Solar Calculators.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] In recent years new PV technologies have come to the forefront in Energy Harvesting such as Dye-Sensitized Solar Cells (DSSC).
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The dyes absorb light much like chlorophyll does in plants.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Electrons released on impact escape to the layer of TiO2 and from there diffuse, through the electrolyte, as the dye can be tuned to the visible spectrum much higher power can be produced.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] At 200 lux a DSSC can provide over 10 μW per cm2.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The piezoelectric effect converts mechanical strain into electric current or voltage.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] This strain can come from many different sources.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Human motion, low-frequency seismic vibrations, and acoustic noise are everyday examples.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Except in rare instances the piezoelectric effect operates in AC requiring time-varying inputs at mechanical resonance to be efficient.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Most piezoelectric electricity sources produce power on the order of milliwatts, too small for system application, but enough for hand-held devices such as some commercially available self-winding wristwatches.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] One proposal is that they are used for micro-scale devices, such as in a device harvesting micro-hydraulic energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] In this device, the flow of pressurized hydraulic fluid drives a reciprocating piston supported by three piezoelectric elements which convert the pressure fluctuations into an alternating current.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] As piezo energy harvesting has been investigated only since the late 1990s, it remains an emerging technology.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Nevertheless, some interesting improvements were made with the self-powered electronic switch at INSA school of engineering, implemented by the spin-off Arveni.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] In 2006, the proof of concept of a battery-less wireless doorbell push button was created, and recently, a product showed that classical wireless wallswitch can be powered by a piezo harvester.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Other industrial applications appeared between 2000 and 2005, to harvest energy from vibration and supply sensors for example, or to harvest energy from shock.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Piezoelectric systems can convert motion from the human body into electrical power.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] DARPA has funded efforts to harness energy from leg and arm motion, shoe impacts, and blood pressure for low level power to implantable or wearable sensors.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The nanobrushes are another example of a piezoelectric energy harvester.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Multiple other nanostructures have been exploited to build an energy-harvesting device, for example, a single crystal PMN-PT nanobelt was fabricated and assembled into a piezoelectric energy harvester in 2016.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Careful design is needed to minimise user discomfort.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] These energy harvesting sources by association affect the body.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The Vibration Energy Scavenging Project is another project that is set up to try to scavenge electrical energy from environmental vibrations and movements.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Microbelt can be used to gather electricity from respiration.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Besides, as the vibration of motion from human comes in three directions, a single piezoelectric cantilever based omni-directional energy harvester is created by using 1:2 internal resonance.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Finally, a millimeter-scale piezoelectric energy harvester has also already been created.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Piezo elements are being embedded in walkways to recover the "people energy" of footsteps.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] They can also be embedded in shoes to recover "walking energy".
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Researchers at MIT developed the first micro-scale piezoelectric energy harvester using thin film PZT in 2005.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Arman Hajati and Sang-Gook Kim invented the Ultra Wide-Bandwidth micro-scale piezoelectric energy harvesting device by exploiting the nonlinear stiffness of a doubly clamped microelectromechanical systems (MEMSs) resonator.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The stretching strain in a doubly clamped beam shows a nonlinear stiffness, which provides a passive feedback and results in amplitude-stiffened Duffing mode resonance.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Typically, piezoelectric cantilevers are adopted for the above-mentioned energy harvesting system.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] One drawback is that the piezoelectric cantilever has gradient strain distribution, i.e., the piezoelectric transducer is not fully utilized.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] To address this issue, triangle shaped and L-shaped cantilever are proposed for uniform strain distribution.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] In 2018, Soochow University researchers reported hybridizing a triboelectric nanogenerator and a silicon solar cell by sharing a mutual electrode.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] This device can collect solar energy *or* convert the mechanical energy of falling raindrops into electricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] UK telecom company Orange UK created an energy harvesting T-shirt and boots.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Other companies have also done the same.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Brothers Pierre Curie and Jacques Curie gave the concept of piezoelectric effect in 1880.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Piezoelectric effect converts mechanical strain into voltage or electric current and generates electric energy from motion, weight, vibration and temperature changes as shown in the figure.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Considering piezoelectric effect in thin film lead zirconate titanate $Pb(Zr,Ti)O_{3}$ PZT, microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) power generating device has been developed.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] However, Aqsa further developed beam-structured electrostatic devices that are more difficult to fabricate than PZT MEMS devices versus a similar because general silicon processing involves many more mask steps that do not require PZT film.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Piezoelectric $d_{31}$ type sensors and actuators have a cantilever beam structure that consists of a membrane bottom electrode, film, piezoelectric film, and top electrode.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] More than *(3~5 masks)* mask steps are required for patterning of each layer while have very low induced voltage.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Pyroelectric crystals that have a unique polar axis and have spontaneous polarization, along which the spontaneous polarization exists.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The special polar axis—crystallophysical axis *X3* – coincides with the axes *L6*,*L4*, *L3*, and *L2* of the crystals or lies in the unique straight plane *P (class "m")*.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Consequently, the electric centers of positive and negative charges are displaced of an elementary cell from equilibrium positions, i.e., the spontaneous polarization of the crystal changes.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Therefore, all considered crystals have spontaneous polarization $Ps=P3$ .
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Since piezoelectric effect in pyroelectric crystals arises as a result of changes in their spontaneous polarization under external effects (electric fields, mechanical stresses).
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] As a result of displacement, Aqsa Abbasi introduced change in the components $\Delta P_{s}$ along all three axes $\Delta P_{s}=(\Delta P_{1},\Delta P_{2},\Delta P_{3})$ .
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Suppose that $\Delta P_{s}=(\Delta P_{1},\Delta P_{2},\Delta P_{3})$ is proportional to the mechanical stresses causing in a first approximation, which results $\Delta P_{i}=diklTkl$ where *Tkl* represents the mechanical stress and *dikl* represents the piezoelectric modules.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] PZT thin films have attracted attention for applications such as force sensors, accelerometers, gyroscopes actuators, tunable optics, micro pumps, ferroelectric RAM, display systems and smart roads, when energy sources are limited, energy harvesting plays an important role in the environment.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Smart roads have the potential to play an important role in power generation.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Embedding piezoelectric material in the road can convert pressure exerted by moving vehicles into voltage and current.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Piezoelectric sensors are most useful in smart-road technologies that can be used to create systems that are intelligent and improve productivity in the long run.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Imagine highways that alert motorists of a traffic jam before it forms.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Or bridges that report when they are at risk of collapse, or an electric grid that fixes itself when blackouts hit.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] For many decades, scientists and experts have argued that the best way to fight congestion is intelligent transportation systems, such as roadside sensors to measure traffic and synchronized traffic lights to control the flow of vehicles.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] But the spread of these technologies has been limited by cost.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] There are also some other smart-technology shovel ready projects which could be deployed fairly quickly, but most of the technologies are still at the development stage and might not be practically available for five years or more.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The pyroelectric effect converts a temperature change into electric current or voltage.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] It is analogous to the piezoelectric effect, which is another type of ferroelectric behavior.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Pyroelectricity requires time-varying inputs and suffers from small power outputs in energy harvesting applications due to its low operating frequencies.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] However, one key advantage of pyroelectrics over thermoelectrics is that many pyroelectric materials are stable up to 1200 °C or higher, enabling energy harvesting from high temperature sources and thus increasing thermodynamic efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] One way to directly convert waste heat into electricity is by executing the Olsen cycle on pyroelectric materials.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The Olsen cycle consists of two isothermal and two isoelectric field processes in the electric displacement-electric field (D-E) diagram.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The principle of the Olsen cycle is to charge a capacitor via cooling under low electric field and to discharge it under heating at higher electric field.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Several pyroelectric converters have been developed to implement the Olsen cycle using conduction, convection, or radiation.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] It has also been established theoretically that pyroelectric conversion based on heat regeneration using an oscillating working fluid and the Olsen cycle can reach Carnot efficiency between a hot and a cold thermal reservoir.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Moreover, recent studies have established polyvinylidene fluoride trifluoroethylene [P(VDF-TrFE)] polymers and lead lanthanum zirconate titanate (PLZT) ceramics as promising pyroelectric materials to use in energy converters due to their large energy densities generated at low temperatures.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Additionally, a pyroelectric scavenging device that does not require time-varying inputs was recently introduced.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The energy-harvesting device uses the edge-depolarizing electric field of a heated pyroelectric to convert heat energy into mechanical energy instead of drawing electric current off two plates attached to the crystal-faces.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] In 1821, Thomas Johann Seebeck discovered that a thermal gradient formed between two dissimilar conductors produces a voltage.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] At the heart of the thermoelectric effect is the fact that a temperature gradient in a conducting material results in heat flow; this results in the diffusion of charge carriers.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The flow of charge carriers between the hot and cold regions in turn creates a voltage difference.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] In 1834, Jean Charles Athanase Peltier discovered that running an electric current through the junction of two dissimilar conductors could, depending on the direction of the current, cause it to act as a heater or cooler.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The heat absorbed or produced is proportional to the current, and the proportionality constant is known as the Peltier coefficient.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Today, due to knowledge of the Seebeck and Peltier effects, thermoelectric materials can be used as heaters, coolers and generators (TEGs).
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Ideal thermoelectric materials have a high Seebeck coefficient, high electrical conductivity, and low thermal conductivity.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Low thermal conductivity is necessary to maintain a high thermal gradient at the junction.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Standard thermoelectric modules manufactured today consist of P- and N-doped bismuth-telluride semiconductors sandwiched between two metallized ceramic plates.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The ceramic plates add rigidity and electrical insulation to the system.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The semiconductors are connected electrically in series and thermally in parallel.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Miniature thermocouples have been developed that convert body heat into electricity and generate 40 μ W at 3 V with a 5-degree temperature gradient, while on the other end of the scale, large thermocouples are used in nuclear RTG batteries.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Practical examples are the finger-heartratemeter by the Holst Centre and the thermogenerators by the Fraunhofer-Gesellschaft.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Thermoelectrics contain no materials that must be replenished.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] One downside to thermoelectric energy conversion is low efficiency (currently less than 10%).
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The development of materials that are able to operate in higher temperature gradients, and that can conduct electricity well without also conducting heat (something that was until recently thought impossible ), will result in increased efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Future work in thermoelectrics could be to convert wasted heat, such as in automobile engine combustion, into electricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] This type of harvesting is based on the changing capacitance of vibration-dependent capacitors.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Vibrations separate the plates of a charged variable capacitor, and mechanical energy is converted into electrical energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Electrostatic energy harvesters need a polarization source to work and to convert mechanical energy from vibrations into electricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The polarization source should be in the order of some hundreds of volts; this greatly complicates the power management circuit.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Another solution consists in using electrets, that are electrically charged dielectrics able to keep the polarization on the capacitor for years.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] It's possible to adapt structures from classical electrostatic induction generators, which also extract energy from variable capacitances, for this purpose.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The resulting devices are self-biasing, and can directly charge batteries, or can produce exponentially growing voltages on storage capacitors, from which energy can be periodically extracted by DC/DC converters.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Magnetic induction refers to the production of an electromotive force (i.e., voltage) in a changing magnetic field.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] This changing magnetic field can be created by motion, either rotation (i.e.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Wiegand effect and Wiegand sensors) or linear movement (i.e. vibration).
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Magnets wobbling on a cantilever are sensitive to even small vibrations and generate microcurrents by moving relative to conductors due to Faraday's law of induction.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] By developing a miniature device of this kind in 2007, a team from the University of Southampton made possible the planting of such a device in environments that preclude having any electrical connection to the outside world.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Sensors in inaccessible places can now generate their own power and transmit data to outside receivers.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] One of the major limitations of the magnetic vibration energy harvester developed at University of Southampton is the size of the generator, in this case approximately one cubic centimeter, which is much too large to integrate into today's mobile technologies.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The complete generator including circuitry is a massive 4 cm by 4 cm by 1 cm nearly the same size as some mobile devices such as the iPod nano.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Further reductions in the dimensions are possible through the integration of new and more flexible materials as the cantilever beam component.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] In 2012, a group at Northwestern University developed a vibration-powered generator out of polymer in the form of a spring.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] This device was able to target the same frequencies as the University of Southampton groups silicon based device but with one third the size of the beam component.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] A new approach to magnetic induction based energy harvesting has also been proposed by using ferrofluids.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The journal article, "Electromagnetic ferrofluid-based energy harvester", discusses the use of ferrofluids to harvest low frequency vibrational energy at 2.2 Hz with a power output of ~80 mW per g.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Quite recently, the change in domain wall pattern with the application of stress has been proposed as a method to harvest energy using magnetic induction.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] In this study, the authors have shown that the applied stress can change the domain pattern in microwires.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Ambient vibrations can cause stress in microwires, which can induce a change in domain pattern and hence change the induction.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Power, of the order of uW/cm2 has been reported.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Commercially successful vibration energy harvesters based on magnetic induction are still relatively few in number.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Examples include products developed by Swedish company ReVibe Energy, a technology spin-out from Saab Group.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Another example is the products developed from the early University of Southampton prototypes by Perpetuum.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] These have to be sufficiently large to generate the power required by wireless sensor nodes (WSN) but in M2M applications this is not normally an issue.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] These harvesters are now being supplied in large volumes to power WSNs made by companies such as GE and Emerson and also for train bearing monitoring systems made by Perpetuum.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Overhead powerline sensors can use magnetic induction to harvest energy directly from the conductor they are monitoring.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Another way of energy harvesting is through the oxidation of blood sugars.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] These energy harvesters are called biobatteries.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] They could be used to power implanted electronic devices (e.g., pacemakers, implanted biosensors for diabetics, implanted active RFID devices, etc.).
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] At present, the Minteer Group of Saint Louis University has created enzymes that could be used to generate power from blood sugars.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] However, the enzymes would still need to be replaced after a few years.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] In 2012, a pacemaker was powered by implantable biofuel cells at Clarkson University under the leadership of Dr.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Tree metabolic energy harvesting is a type of bio-energy harvesting.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Voltree has developed a method for harvesting energy from trees.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] These energy harvesters are being used to power remote sensors and mesh networks as the basis for a long term deployment system to monitor forest fires and weather in the forest.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] According to Voltree's website, the useful life of such a device should be limited only by the lifetime of the tree to which it is attached.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] A small test network was recently deployed in a US National Park forest.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Other sources of energy from trees include capturing the physical movement of the tree in a generator.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Theoretical analysis of this source of energy shows some promise in powering small electronic devices.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] A practical device based on this theory has been built and successfully powered a sensor node for a year.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Soil microbial fuel cells harvest electrical energy from the anaerobic respiration of naturally occurring soil bacteria, which provides the oxidation reaction at the anode.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Soil microbial fuel cells can output microwatts of power, and have been used in both classroom demonstrations and to power analog radar sensors.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] A metamaterial-based device wirelessly converts a 900 MHz microwave signal to 7.3 volts of direct current (greater than that of a USB device).
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The device can be tuned to harvest other signals including Wi-Fi signals, satellite signals, or even sound signals.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The experimental device used a series of five fiberglass and copper conductors.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Conversion efficiency reached 37 percent.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] When traditional antennas are close to each other in space they interfere with each other.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] But since RF power goes down by the cube of the distance, the amount of power is very very small.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] While the claim of 7.3 volts is grand, the measurement is for an open circuit.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Since the power is so low, there can be almost no current when any load is attached.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The pressure of the atmosphere changes naturally over time from temperature changes and weather patterns.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Devices with a sealed chamber can use these pressure differences to extract energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] This has been used to provide power for mechanical clocks such as the Atmos clock.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] A relatively new concept of generating energy is to generate energy from oceans.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Large masses of waters are present on the planet which carry with them great amounts of energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The energy in this case can be generated by tidal streams, ocean waves, difference in salinity and also difference in temperature.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] As of 2018, efforts are underway to harvest energy this way.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] United States Navy recently was able to generate electricity using difference in temperatures present in the ocean.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] One method to use the temperature difference across different levels of the thermocline in the ocean is by using a thermal energy harvester that is equipped with a material that changes phase while in different temperatures regions.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] This is typically a polymer-based material that can handle reversible heat treatments.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] When the material is changing phase, the energy differential is converted into mechanical energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The materials used will need to be able to alter phases, from liquid to solid, depending on the position of the thermocline underwater.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] These phase change materials within thermal energy harvesting units would be an ideal way to recharge or power an unmanned underwater vehicle (UUV) being that it will rely on the warm and cold water already present in large bodies of water; minimizing the need for standard battery recharging.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Capturing this energy would allow for longer-term missions since the need to be collected or return for charging can be eliminated.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] This is also a very environmentally friendly method of powering underwater vehicles.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] There are no emissions that come from utilizing a phase change fluid, and it will likely have a longer lifespan than that of a standard battery.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Electroactive polymers (EAPs) have been proposed for harvesting energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] These polymers have a large strain, elastic energy density, and high energy conversion efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] The total weight of systems based on EAPs (electroactive polymers) is proposed to be significantly lower than those based on piezoelectric materials.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Nanogenerators, such as the one made by Georgia Tech, could provide a new way for powering devices without batteries.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] As of 2008, it only generates some dozen nanowatts, which is too low for any practical application.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Noise has been the subject of a proposal by NiPS Laboratory in Italy to harvest wide spectrum low scale vibrations via a nonlinear dynamical mechanism that can improve harvester efficiency up to a factor 4 compared to traditional linear harvesters.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Asymmetries in bistable energy harvesters can significantly affect dynamic performance and harvested power, especially under nonlinear piezoelectric coupling and parametric variability.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Recent studies show that while asymmetries may degrade response in certain regimes, they can also be exploited—through sloping angle tuning and robust parameter selection—to enhance energy conversion and outperform symmetric designs.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] Combinations of different types of energy harvesters can further reduce dependence on batteries, particularly in environments where the available ambient energy types change periodically.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/energy-harvesting] This type of complementary balanced energy harvesting has the potential to increase reliability of wireless sensor systems for structural health monitoring.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The piezoelectric effect results from the linear electromechanical interaction between the mechanical and electrical states in crystalline materials with no inversion symmetry.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The piezoelectric effect is a reversible process: materials exhibiting the piezoelectric effect also exhibit the reverse piezoelectric effect, the internal generation of a mechanical strain resulting from an applied electric field.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] For example, lead zirconate titanate crystals will generate measurable piezoelectricity when their static structure is deformed by about 0.1% of the original dimension.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Conversely, those same crystals will change about 0.1% of their static dimension when an external electric field is applied.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The inverse piezoelectric effect is used in the production of ultrasound waves.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] French physicists Jacques and Pierre Curie discovered piezoelectricity in 1880.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] It forms the basis for scanning probe microscopes that resolve images at the scale of atoms.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] It is used in the pickups of some electronically amplified guitars and as triggers in most modern electronic drums.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The piezoelectric effect also finds everyday uses, such as generating sparks to ignite gas cooking and heating devices, torches, and cigarette lighters.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The word *piezoelectricity* means electricity resulting from pressure.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] It is derived from Ancient Greek πιέζω*(*piézō*)* 'to squeeze or press' and ἤλεκτρον*(*ḗlektron*)* 'amber' (an ancient source of static electricity).
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The German form of the word (*Piezoelektrizität*) was coined in 1881 by the German physicist Wilhelm Gottlieb Hankel; the English word was derived from German in 1883.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The pyroelectric effect, by which a material generates an electric potential in response to a temperature change, was studied by Carl Linnaeus and Franz Aepinus in the mid-18th century.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Drawing on this knowledge, both René Just Haüy and Antoine César Becquerel posited a relationship between mechanical stress and electric charge; however, experiments by both proved inconclusive.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The first demonstration of the direct piezoelectric effect was in 1880 by the brothers Pierre Curie and Jacques Curie.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Quartz and Rochelle salt exhibited the most piezoelectricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The Curies, however, did not predict the converse piezoelectric effect.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The converse effect was mathematically deduced from fundamental thermodynamic principles by Gabriel Lippmann in 1881.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The Curies immediately confirmed the existence of the converse effect, and went on to obtain quantitative proof of the complete reversibility of electro-elasto-mechanical deformations in piezoelectric crystals.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] For the next few decades, piezoelectricity remained something of a laboratory curiosity, though it was a vital tool in the discovery of polonium and radium by Pierre and Marie Curie in 1898.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] More work was done to explore and define the crystal structures that exhibited piezoelectricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] This culminated in 1910 with the publication of Woldemar Voigt's *Lehrbuch der Kristallphysik* (*Textbook on Crystal Physics*), which described the 20 natural crystal classes capable of piezoelectricity, and rigorously defined the piezoelectric constants using tensor analysis.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The first practical application for piezoelectric devices was sonar, first developed during World War I.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The superior performance of piezoelectric devices, operating at ultrasonic frequencies, superseded the earlier Fessenden oscillator.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] In France in 1917, Paul Langevin and his coworkers developed an ultrasonic submarine detector.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The detector consisted of a transducer, made of thin quartz crystals carefully glued between two steel plates, and a hydrophone to detect the returned echo.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] By emitting a high-frequency pulse from the transducer, and measuring the amount of time it takes to hear an echo from the sound waves bouncing off an object, one can calculate the distance to that object.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectric devices found homes in many fields.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Ceramic phonograph cartridges simplified player design, were cheap and accurate, and made record players cheaper to maintain and easier to build.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The development of the ultrasonic transducer allowed for easy measurement of viscosity and elasticity in fluids and solids, resulting in huge advances in materials research.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Ultrasonic time-domain reflectometers (which send an ultrasonic pulse through a material and measure reflections from discontinuities) could find flaws inside cast metal and stone objects, improving structural safety.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] During World War II, independent research groups in the United States, USSR, and Japan discovered a new class of synthetic materials, called ferroelectrics, which exhibited piezoelectric constants many times higher than natural materials.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] This led to intense research to develop barium titanate and later lead zirconate titanate materials with specific properties for particular applications.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] One significant example of the use of piezoelectric crystals was developed by Bell Telephone Laboratories.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Lack, working in radio telephony in the engineering department, developed the "AT cut" crystal, a crystal that operated through a wide range of temperatures.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Lack's crystal did not need the heavy accessories previous crystal used, facilitating its use on the aircraft.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] This development allowed Allied air forces to engage in coordinated mass attacks through the use of aviation radio.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Development of piezoelectric devices and materials in the United States was kept within the companies doing the development, mostly due to the wartime beginnings of the field, and in the interests of securing profitable patents.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] New materials were the first to be developed—quartz crystals were the first commercially exploited piezoelectric material, but scientists searched for higher-performance materials.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Despite the advances in materials and the maturation of manufacturing processes, the United States market did not grow as quickly as Japan's did.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Without many new applications, the growth of the United States' piezoelectric industry suffered.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] In contrast, Japanese manufacturers shared their information, quickly overcoming technical and manufacturing challenges and creating new markets.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] In Japan, a temperature stable crystal cut was developed by Issac Koga.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Japanese efforts in materials research created piezoceramic materials competitive to the United States materials but free of expensive patent restrictions.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Ultrasonic transducers that transmit sound waves through air had existed for quite some time but first saw major commercial use in early television remote controls.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] These transducers now are mounted on several car models as an echolocation device, helping the driver determine the distance from the car to any objects that may be in its path.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The nature of the piezoelectric effect is closely related to the occurrence of electric dipole moments in solids.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] These may be either induced for ions on crystal lattice sites with asymmetric charge surroundings (as in BaTiO3 and PZTs) or directly carried by molecular groups (as in cane sugar).
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The dipole density or polarization (dimensionality [C·m/m3] ) may easily be calculated for crystals by summing up the dipole moments per volume of the crystallographic unit cell.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] As every dipole is a vector, the dipole density ***P*** is a vector field.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Dipoles near each other tend to be aligned in regions called Weiss domains.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The domains are usually randomly oriented, but can be aligned using the process of *poling* (not the same as magnetic poling), a process by which a strong electric field is applied across the material, usually at elevated temperatures.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Not all piezoelectric materials can be poled.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Of importance for the piezoelectric effect is the change of polarization ***P*** when applying a mechanical stress.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] This might either be caused by a reconfiguration of the dipole-inducing surrounding or by re-orientation of molecular dipole moments under the influence of the external stress.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectricity may then manifest in a variation of the polarization strength, its direction or both, with the details depending on: 1. the orientation of ***P*** within the crystal; 2. crystal symmetry; and 3. the applied mechanical stress.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The change in ***P*** appears as a variation of surface charge density upon the crystal faces, i.e. as a variation of the electric field extending between the faces caused by a change in dipole density in the bulk.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] For example, a 1 cm3 cube of quartz with 2 kN (500 lbf) of correctly applied force can produce a voltage of 12500 V.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectric materials also show the opposite effect, called the **converse piezoelectric effect**, where the application of an electrical field creates mechanical deformation in the crystal.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] where ${\mathfrak {d}}$ is the piezoelectric tensor and the superscript t stands for its transpose.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] where [*d*] is the matrix for the direct piezoelectric effect and [*d*t] is the matrix for the converse piezoelectric effect.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The superscript *E* indicates a zero, or constant, electric field; the superscript *T* indicates a zero, or constant, stress field; and the superscript t stands for transposition of a matrix.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Notice that the third order tensor ${\mathfrak {d}}$ maps vectors into symmetric matrices.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] There are no non-trivial rotation-invariant tensors that have this property, which is why there are no isotropic piezoelectric materials.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] where the first equation represents the relationship for the converse piezoelectric effect and the latter for the direct piezoelectric effect.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Although the above equations are the most used form in literature, some comments about the notation are necessary.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Generally, *D* and *E* are vectors, that is, Cartesian tensors of rank 1; and permittivity *ε* is a Cartesian tensor of rank 2.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Strain and stress are, in principle, also rank-2 tensors.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] But conventionally, because strain and stress are all symmetric tensors, the subscript of strain and stress can be relabeled in the following fashion: 11 → 1; 22 → 2; 33 → 3; 23 → 4; 13 → 5; 12 → 6.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] (Different conventions may be used by different authors in literature.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] For example, some use 12 → 4; 23 → 5; 31 → 6 instead.) That is why *S* and *T* appear to have the "vector form" of six components.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Consequently, *s* appears to be a 6-by-6 matrix instead of a rank-3 tensor.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Such a relabeled notation is often called Voigt notation.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Whether the shear strain components *S*4, *S*5, *S*6 are tensor components or engineering strains is another question.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] In the equation above, they must be engineering strains for the 6,6 coefficient of the compliance matrix to be written as shown, i.e., 2(*s**E* 11 − *s**E* 12).
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Engineering shear strains are double the value of the corresponding tensor shear, such as *S*6 = 2*S*12 and so on.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] This also means that *s*66 = ⁠1/*G*12⁠, where *G*12 is the shear modulus.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] where the first set of four terms corresponds to the direct piezoelectric effect and the second set of four terms corresponds to the converse piezoelectric effect.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The equality between the direct piezoelectric tensor and the transpose of the converse piezoelectric tensor originates from the Maxwell relations of thermodynamics.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] For those piezoelectric crystals for which the polarization is of the crystal-field induced type, a formalism has been worked out that allows for the calculation of piezoelectrical coefficients *dij* from electrostatic lattice constants or higher-order Madelung constants.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Of the 32 crystal classes, 21 are non-centrosymmetric (not having a centre of symmetry), and of these, 20 exhibit direct piezoelectricity (the 21st is the cubic class 432).
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Ten of these represent the polar crystal classes, which show a spontaneous polarization without mechanical stress due to a non-vanishing electric dipole moment associated with their unit cell, and which exhibit pyroelectricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] If the dipole moment can be reversed by applying an external electric field, the material is said to be ferroelectric.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] For polar crystals, for which ***P*** ≠ 0 holds without applying a mechanical load, the piezoelectric effect manifests itself by changing the magnitude or the direction of ***P*** or both.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] For the nonpolar but piezoelectric crystals, on the other hand, a polarization ***P*** different from zero is only elicited by applying a mechanical load.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] For them the stress can be imagined to transform the material from a nonpolar crystal class (***P*** = 0) to a polar one, having ***P*** ≠ 0.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Many materials exhibit piezoelectricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Ceramics with randomly oriented grains must be ferroelectric to exhibit piezoelectricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Macroscopic piezoelectricity is possible in textured polycrystalline non-ferroelectric piezoelectric materials, such as AlN and ZnO.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The fabrication of lead-free piezoceramics pose multiple challenges, from an environmental standpoint and their ability to replicate the properties of their lead-based counterparts.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] By removing the lead component of the piezoceramic, the risk of toxicity to humans decreases, but the mining and extraction of the materials can be harmful to the environment.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Most of the concerns with KNN, specifically its Nb2O5 component, are in the early phase of its life cycle before it reaches manufacturers.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Since the harmful impacts are focused on these early phases, some actions can be taken to minimize the effects.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Returning the land as close to its original form after Nb2O5 mining via dam deconstruction or replacing a stockpile of utilizable soil are known aids for any extraction event.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] For minimizing air quality effects, modeling and simulation still needs to occur to fully understand what mitigation methods are required.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The extraction of lead-free piezoceramic components has not grown to a significant scale at this time, but from early analysis, experts encourage caution when it comes to environmental effects.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Fabricating lead-free piezoceramics faces the challenge of maintaining the performance and stability of their lead-based counterparts.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] In general, the main fabrication challenge is creating the "morphotropic phase boundaries (MPBs)" that provide the materials with their stable piezoelectric properties without introducing the "polymorphic phase boundaries (PPBs)" that decrease the temperature stability of the material.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] New phase boundaries are created by varying additive concentrations so that the phase transition temperatures converge at room temperature.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The introduction of the MPB improves piezoelectric properties, but if a PPB is introduced, the material becomes negatively affected by temperature.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Research is ongoing to control the type of phase boundaries that are introduced through phase engineering, diffusing phase transitions, domain engineering, and chemical modification.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] A piezoelectric potential can be created in any bulk or nanostructured semiconductor crystal having non central symmetry, such as the Group III–V and II–VI materials, due to polarization of ions under applied stress and strain.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] This property is common to both the zincblende and wurtzite crystal structures.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] To first order, there is only one independent piezoelectric coefficient in zincblende, called e14, coupled to shear components of the strain.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] In wurtzite, there are instead three independent piezoelectric coefficients: *e*31, *e*33 and *e*15.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The semiconductors where the strongest piezoelectricity is observed are those commonly found in the wurtzite structure, i.e.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] GaN, InN, AlN and ZnO (see piezotronics).
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Since 2006, there have also been a number of reports of strong non linear piezoelectric effects in polar semiconductors.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Such effects are generally recognized to be at least important if not of the same order of magnitude as the first order approximation.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The piezo-response of polymers is not as high as the response for ceramics; however, polymers hold properties that ceramics do not.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Over the last few decades, non-toxic, piezoelectric polymers have been studied and applied due to their flexibility and smaller acoustical impedance.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Other properties that make these materials significant include their biocompatibility, biodegradability, low cost, and low power consumption compared to other piezo-materials (ceramics, etc.).
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectric polymers can be classified by bulk polymers, voided charged polymers ("piezoelectrets"), and polymer composites.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] A piezo-response observed by bulk polymers is mostly due to its molecular structure.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] There are two types of bulk polymers: amorphous and semi-crystalline.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Examples of semi-crystalline polymers are polyvinylidene fluoride (PVDF) and its copolymers, polyamides, and parylene-C.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Non-crystalline polymers, such as polyimide and polyvinylidene chloride (PVDC), fall under amorphous bulk polymers.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Voided charged polymers exhibit the piezoelectric effect due to charge induced by poling of a porous polymeric film.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Under an electric field, charges form on the surface of the voids forming dipoles.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Electric responses can be caused by any deformation of these voids.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The piezoelectric effect can also be observed in polymer composites by integrating piezoelectric ceramic particles into a polymer film.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] A polymer does not have to be piezo-active to be an effective material for a polymer composite.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] In this case, a material could be made up of an inert matrix with a separate piezo-active component.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] PVDF exhibits piezoelectricity several times greater than quartz.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The piezo-response observed from PVDF is about 20–30 pC/N.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] That is an order of 5–50 times less than that of piezoelectric ceramic lead zirconate titanate (PZT).
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The thermal stability of the piezoelectric effect of polymers in the PVDF family (i.e. vinylidene fluoride co-poly trifluoroethylene) goes up to 125 °C.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Some applications of PVDF are pressure sensors, hydrophones, and shock wave sensors.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Due to their flexibility, piezoelectric composites have been proposed as energy harvesters and nanogenerators.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] In 2018, it was reported by Zhu et al. that a piezoelectric response of about 17 pC/N could be obtained from PDMS/PZT nanocomposite at 60% porosity.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Another PDMS nanocomposite was reported in 2017, in which BaTiO3 was integrated into PDMS to make a stretchable, transparent nanogenerator for self-powered physiological monitoring.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] In 2016, polar molecules were introduced into a polyurethane foam in which high responses of up to 244 pC/N were reported.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Most materials exhibit at least weak piezoelectric responses.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Trivial examples include sucrose (table sugar), DNA, and viral proteins, including those from bacteriophage.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] An actuator based on wood fibers (cellulose fibers) has been reported.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] D33 responses for cellular polypropylene are around 200 pC/N.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Some applications of cellular polypropylene are musical key pads, microphones, and ultrasound-based echolocation systems.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Recently, a single amino acid, β-glycine, displayed a high piezoelectric response of 178 pm V−1 compared with other biological materials.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Ionic liquids were recently identified as the first piezoelectric liquid.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Direct piezoelectricity of some substances, like quartz, can generate potential differences of thousands of volts.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The principle of operation of a piezoelectric sensor is that a physical dimension, transformed into a force, acts on two opposing faces of the sensing element.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Depending on the design of a sensor, different "modes" to load the piezoelectric element can be used: longitudinal, transversal and shear.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Detection of pressure variations in the form of sound is the most common sensor application, e.g. piezoelectric microphones (sound waves bend the piezoelectric material, creating a changing voltage) and piezoelectric pickups for acoustic-electric guitars.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] A piezo sensor attached to the body of an instrument is known as a contact microphone.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectric sensors especially are used with high frequency sound in ultrasonic transducers for medical imaging and also industrial nondestructive testing (NDT).
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] For many sensing techniques, the sensor can act as both a sensor and an actuator—often the term *transducer* is preferred when the device acts in this dual capacity, but most piezo devices have this property of reversibility whether it is used or not.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Ultrasonic transducers, for example, can inject ultrasound waves into the body, receive the returned wave, and convert it to an electrical signal (a voltage).
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Most medical ultrasound transducers are piezoelectric.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] As very high electric fields correspond to only tiny changes in the width of the crystal, this width can be changed with better-than-μm precision, making piezo crystals the most important tool for positioning objects with extreme accuracy—thus their use in actuators.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Multilayer ceramics, using layers thinner than 100 μm, allow reaching high electric fields with voltage lower than 150 V.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] These ceramics are used within two kinds of actuators: direct piezo actuators and amplified piezoelectric actuators.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] While direct actuator's stroke is generally lower than 100 μm, amplified piezo actuators can reach millimeter strokes.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The piezoelectrical properties of quartz are useful as a standard of frequency.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Aside from the stepping stick-slip motor, all these motors work on the same principle.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Driven by dual orthogonal vibration modes with a phase difference of 90°, the contact point between two surfaces vibrates in an elliptical path, producing a frictional force between the surfaces.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Usually, one surface is fixed, causing the other to move.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] In most piezoelectric motors, the piezoelectric crystal is excited by a sine wave signal at the resonant frequency of the motor.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Using the resonance effect, a much lower voltage can be used to produce a high vibration amplitude.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] A stick-slip motor works using the inertia of a mass and the friction of a clamp.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Some are used for camera sensor displacement, thus allowing an anti-shake function.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Different teams of researchers have been investigating ways to reduce vibrations in materials by attaching piezo elements to the material.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] When the material is bent by a vibration in one direction, the vibration-reduction system responds to the bend and sends electric power to the piezo element to bend in the other direction.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Applications to flexible structures, such as shells and plates, have also been studied for nearly three decades.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Piezosurgery is a minimally invasive technique that aims to cut a target tissue with little damage to neighboring tissues.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] For example, Hoigne *et al.* uses frequencies in the range 25–29 kHz, causing microvibrations of 60–210 μm.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] It has the ability to cut mineralized tissue without cutting neurovascular tissue and other soft tissue, thereby maintaining a blood-free operating area, better visibility and greater precision.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] In 2019, Pernas-Salomón and Shmuel developed a dynamic homogenization method by which they were the first to show that piezoelectric composites exhibit an effective coupling between linear momentum and the electric field, which they termed electro-momentum coupling.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Because homogeneous piezoelectric materials do not exhibit this coupling, such composites belong to the class of metamaterials—artificial media engineered to display extraordinary effective properties, in magnitude or in kind.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Electro-momentum coupling is analogous to Willis coupling in elastic composites, which couples linear momentum to strain and was discovered by J.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] The local part of these couplings—like piezoelectric coupling—emerges from broken symmetries.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectric metamaterials with electro-momentum coupling offer a mechanism for wave manipulation akin to Willis coupling: they impart a direction-dependent phase shift that enables wavefront shaping, with the added advantage of electrical tunability.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] A **rectenna** (***rect*ifying ant*enna***) is a special type of receiving antenna that is used for converting electromagnetic energy into direct current (DC) electricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] They are used in wireless power transmission systems that transmit power by radio waves.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] A simple rectenna element consists of a dipole antenna with a diode connected across the dipole elements.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] The diode rectifies the AC induced in the antenna by the microwaves, to produce DC power, which powers a load connected across the diode.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] Schottky diodes are usually used because they have the lowest voltage drop and highest speed and therefore have the lowest power losses due to conduction and switching.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] Large rectennas consist of arrays of many power receiving elements such as dipole antennas.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] The invention of the rectenna in the 1960s made long distance wireless power transmission feasible.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] The rectenna was invented in 1964 and patented in 1969 by US electrical engineer William C.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] Brown, who demonstrated it with a model helicopter powered by microwaves transmitted from the ground, received by an attached rectenna.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] Since the 1970s, one of the major motivations for rectenna research has been to develop a receiving antenna for proposed solar power satellites, which would harvest energy from sunlight in space with solar cells and beam it down to Earth as microwaves to huge rectenna arrays.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] A proposed military application is to power drone reconnaissance aircraft with microwaves beamed from the ground, allowing them to stay aloft for long periods.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] In recent years, interest has turned to using rectennas as power sources for small wireless microelectronic devices.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] The largest current use of rectennas is in RFID tags, proximity cards and contactless smart cards, which contain an integrated circuit (IC) which is powered by a small rectenna element.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] When the device is brought near an electronic reader unit, radio waves from the reader are received by the rectenna, powering up the IC, which transmits its data back to the reader.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] The simplest crystal radio receiver, employing an antenna and a demodulating diode (rectifier), is actually a rectenna, although it discards the DC component before sending the signal to the headphones.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] People living near strong radio transmitters would occasionally discover that with a long receiving antenna, they could get enough electric power to light a light bulb.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] However, this example uses only one antenna having a limited capture area.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] A rectenna array uses multiple antennas spread over a wide area to capture more energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] Researchers are experimenting with the use of rectennas to power sensors in remote areas and distributed networks of sensors, especially for IoT applications.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] RF rectennas are used for several forms of wireless power transfer.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] In the microwave range, experimental devices have reached a power conversion efficiency of 85–90%.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] The record conversion efficiency for a rectenna is 90.6% for 2.45 GHz, with lower efficiency of about 82% achieved at 5.82 GHz.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] In principle, similar devices, scaled down to the proportions used in nanotechnology, can be used to convert light directly into electricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] This type of device is called an *optical rectenna* (or "nantenna").
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] Theoretically, high efficiencies can be maintained as the device shrinks, but to date efficiency has been limited, and so far there has not been convincing evidence that rectification has been achieved at optical frequencies.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] The University of Missouri previously reported on work to develop low-cost, high-efficiency optical-frequency rectennas.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] Other prototype devices were investigated in a collaboration between the University of Connecticut and Penn State Altoona using a grant from the National Science Foundation.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] With the use of atomic layer deposition it has been suggested that conversion efficiencies of solar energy to electricity higher than 70% could eventually be achieved.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] Creating an ultra-fast diode capable of rectifying the high frequency oscillations, at frequency of c.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] Below are a few examples of potential paths to creating diodes that would be fast enough to rectify optical and near-optical radiation.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] A promising path towards creating these ultrafast diodes has been in the form of "geometric diodes".
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] Graphene geometric diodes have been reported to rectify terahertz radiation.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] In April 2020, geometric diodes were reported in silicon nanowires.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/rectenna] The wires were shown experimentally to rectify up to 40 GHz, that result was the limit of the instrument used, and the wires theoretically may be able to rectify signals in the terahertz region as well.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] A **thermoelectric generator** (**TEG**), also called a **Seebeck generator**, is a solid state device that converts heat (driven by temperature differences) directly into electrical energy through a phenomenon called the *Seebeck effect* (a form of thermoelectric effect).
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Thermoelectric generators function like heat engines, but are less bulky and have no moving parts.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] However, TEGs are typically more expensive and less efficient.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] When the same principle is used in reverse to create a heat gradient from an electric current, it is called a thermoelectric (or Peltier) cooler.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Thermoelectric generators could be used in power plants and factories to convert waste heat into additional electrical power and in automobiles as automotive thermoelectric generators (ATGs) to increase fuel efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Radioisotope thermoelectric generators use radioisotopes to generate the required temperature difference to power space probes.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Thermoelectric generators can also be used alongside solar panels.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] In 1821, Thomas Johann Seebeck discovered that a thermal gradient formed between two different conductors can produce electricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] At the heart of the thermoelectric effect is that a temperature gradient in a conducting material results in heat flow; this results in the diffusion of charge carriers.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] In 1834, Jean Charles Athanase Peltier discovered the reverse effect, that running an electric current through the junction of two dissimilar conductors could, depending on the direction of the current, cause it to act as a heater or cooler.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] George Cove had accidentally invented a photovoltaic panel, despite intending to invent a thermoelectric generator with thermocouples, in 1909.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] He notes that heat alone didn't produce any power, only incident light, but he had no explanation for how it could be working.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] The operational principle is now understood to have been a very simple form of Schottky junction.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] The typical efficiency of TEGs is around 5–8%, although it can be higher.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Older devices used bimetallic junctions and were bulky.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] More recent devices use highly doped semiconductors made from bismuth telluride (Bi2Te3), lead telluride (PbTe), calcium manganese oxide (Ca2Mn3O8), or combinations thereof, depending on application temperature.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] These are solid-state devices and unlike dynamos have no moving parts, with the occasional exception of a fan or pump to improve heat transfer.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] If the hot region is around 1273K and the ZT values of 3 - 4 are implemented, the efficiency is approximately 33-37%; allowing TEG's to compete with certain heat engine efficiencies.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Thermoelectric power generators consist of three major components: thermoelectric materials, thermoelectric modules and thermoelectric systems that interface with the heat source.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Thermoelectric materials generate power directly from the heat by converting temperature differences into electric voltage.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] These materials must have both high electrical conductivity (σ) and low thermal conductivity (κ) to be good thermoelectric materials.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Having low thermal conductivity ensures that when one side is made hot, the other side stays cold, which helps to generate a large voltage while in a temperature gradient.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] The measure of the magnitude of electrons flow in response to a temperature difference across that material is given by the Seebeck coefficient (S).
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] The efficiency of a given material to produce a thermoelectric power is simply estimated by its "figure of merit" zT = S2σT/κ.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] For many years, the main three semiconductors known to have both low thermal conductivity and high power factor were bismuth telluride (Bi2Te3), lead telluride (PbTe), and silicon germanium (SiGe).
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Some of these materials have somewhat rare elements which make them expensive.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Today, the thermal conductivity of semiconductors can be lowered without affecting their high electrical properties using nanotechnology.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] This can be achieved by creating nanoscale features such as particles, wires or interfaces in bulk semiconductor materials.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] However, the manufacturing processes of nano-materials are still challenging.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Thermoelectric generators are all-solid-state devices that do not require any fluids for fuel or cooling, making them non-orientation dependent allowing for use in zero-gravity or deep-sea applications.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] The solid-state design allows for operation in severe environments.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Thermoelectric generators have no moving parts which produce a more reliable device that does not require maintenance for long periods.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] The durability and environmental stability have made thermoelectrics a favorite for NASA's deep space explorers among other applications.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] One of the key advantages of thermoelectric generators outside of such specialized applications is that they can potentially be integrated into existing technologies to boost efficiency and reduce environmental impact by producing usable power from waste heat.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] A thermoelectric module is a circuit containing thermoelectric materials which generate electricity from heat directly.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] A thermoelectric module consists of two dissimilar thermoelectric materials joined at their ends: an n-type (with negative charge carriers), and a p-type (with positive charge carriers) semiconductor.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Direct electric current will flow in the circuit when there is a temperature difference between the ends of the materials.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] where $\sigma$ is the local conductivity, S is the Seebeck coefficient (also known as thermopower), a property of the local material, and $\nabla T$ is the temperature gradient.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] In application, thermoelectric modules in power generation work in very tough mechanical and thermal conditions.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Because they operate in a very high-temperature gradient, the modules are subject to large thermally induced stresses and strains for long periods.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] They also are subject to mechanical fatigue caused by a large number of thermal cycles.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Thus, the junctions and materials must be selected so that they survive these tough mechanical and thermal conditions.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Also, the module must be designed such that the two thermoelectric materials are thermally in parallel, but electrically in series.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] The efficiency of a thermoelectric module is greatly affected by the geometry of its design.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Thermoelectric generators are made of several thermopiles, each consisting of many thermocouples made of a connected n-type and p-type material.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] The arrangement of the thermocouples is typically in three main designs: planar, vertical, and mixed.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Planar design involves thermocouples put onto a substrate horizontally between the heat source and cool side, resulting in the ability to create longer and thinner thermocouples, thereby increasing the thermal resistance and temperature gradient and eventually increasing voltage output.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Vertical design has thermocouples arranged vertically between the hot and cool plates, leading to high integration of thermocouples as well as a high output voltage, making this design the most widely used design commercially.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] The mixed design has the thermocouples arranged laterally on the substrate while the heat flow is vertical between plates.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Microcavities under the hot contacts of the device allow for a temperature gradient, which allows for the substrate's thermal conductivity to affect the gradient and efficiency of the device.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] For microelectromechanical systems, TEGs can be designed on the scale of handheld devices to use body heat in the form of thin films.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Flexible TEGs for wearable electronics are able to be made with novel polymers through additive manufacturing or thermal spraying processes.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Cylindrical TEGs for using heat from vehicle exhaust pipes can also be made using circular thermocouples arranged in a cylinder.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Many designs for TEGs can be made for the different devices they are applied to.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Using thermoelectric modules, a thermoelectric system generates power by taking in heat from a source such as a hot exhaust flue.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] To operate, the system needs a large temperature gradient, which is not easy in real-world applications.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] The cold side must be cooled by air or water.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Heat exchangers are used on both sides of the modules to supply this heating and cooling.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] There are many challenges in designing a reliable TEG system that operates at high temperatures.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Achieving high efficiency in the system requires extensive engineering design to balance between the heat flow through the modules and maximizing the temperature gradient across them.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] To do this, designing heat exchanger technologies in the system is one of the most important aspects of TEG engineering.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] In addition, the system requires to minimize the thermal losses due to the interfaces between materials at several places.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Another challenging constraint is avoiding large pressure drops between the heating and cooling sources.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] If AC power is required (such as for powering equipment designed to run from AC mains power), the DC power from the TE modules must be passed through an inverter, which lowers efficiency and adds to the cost and complexity of the system.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Only a few known materials to date are identified as thermoelectric materials.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Most thermoelectric materials today have a zT, the figure of merit, value of around 1, such as in bismuth telluride (Bi2Te3) at room temperature and lead telluride (PbTe) at 500–700 K.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] However, in order to be competitive with other power generation systems, TEG materials should have a zT of 2–3.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Most research in thermoelectric materials has focused on increasing the Seebeck coefficient (S) and reducing the thermal conductivity, especially by manipulating the nanostructure of the thermoelectric materials.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Because both the thermal and electrical conductivity correlate with the charge carriers, new means must be introduced in order to conciliate the contradiction between high electrical conductivity and low thermal conductivity, as is needed.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] When selecting materials for thermoelectric generation, a number of other factors need to be considered.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] During operation, ideally, the thermoelectric generator has a large temperature gradient across it.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Thermal expansion will then introduce stress in the device which may cause fracture of the thermoelectric legs or separation from the coupling material.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] The mechanical properties of the materials must be considered and the coefficient of thermal expansion of the n and p-type material must be matched reasonably well.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] In segmented thermoelectric generators, the material's compatibility must also be considered to avoid incompatibility of relative current, defined as the ratio of electrical current to diffusion heat current, between segment layers.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] When the compatibility factor from one segment to the next differs by more than a factor of about two, the device will not operate efficiently.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] The material parameters determining s (as well as zT) are temperature-dependent, so the compatibility factor may change from the hot side to the cold side of the device, even in one segment.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] This behavior is referred to as self-compatibility and may become important in devices designed for wide-temperature application.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Many TEG materials are employed in commercial applications today.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Highest temperatures material (up to 1300 K): materials fabricated from silicon-germanium (SiGe) alloys.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Although these materials still remain the cornerstone for commercial and practical applications in thermoelectric power generation, significant advances have been made in synthesizing new materials and fabricating material structures with improved thermoelectric performance.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Recent research has focused on improving the material's figure-of-merit (zT), and hence the conversion efficiency, by reducing the lattice thermal conductivity.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Researchers are trying to develop new thermoelectric materials for power generation by improving the figure-of-merit zT.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] One example of these materials is the semiconductor compound ß-Zn4Sb3, which possesses an exceptionally low thermal conductivity and exhibits a maximum zT of 1.3 at a temperature of 670K.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] This material is also relatively inexpensive and stable up to this temperature in a vacuum, and can be a good alternative in the temperature range between materials based on Bi2Te3 and PbTe.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Among the most exciting developments in thermoelectric materials was the development of single crystal tin selenide which produced a record zT of 2.6 in one direction.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Other new materials of interest include Skutterudites, Tetrahedrites, and rattling ions crystals.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Besides improving the figure-of-merit, there is increasing focus to develop new materials by increasing the electrical power output, decreasing cost and developing environmentally friendly materials.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] For example, when the fuel cost is low or almost free, such as in waste heat recovery, then the cost per watt is only determined by the power per unit area and the operating period.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] As a result, it has initiated a search for materials with high power output rather than conversion efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] For example, the rare earth compounds YbAl3 has a low figure-of-merit, but it has a power output of at least double that of any other material, and can operate over the temperature range of a waste heat source.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] To increase the figure of merit (zT), a material's thermal conductivity should be minimized while its electrical conductivity and Seebeck coefficient is maximized.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] In most cases, methods to increase or decrease one property result in the same effect on other properties due to their interdependence.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] A novel processing technique exploits the scattering of different phonon frequencies to selectively reduce lattice thermal conductivity without the typical negative effects on electrical conductivity from the simultaneous increased scattering of electrons.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] In a bismuth antimony tellurium ternary system, liquid-phase sintering is used to produce low-energy semicoherent grain boundaries, which do not have a significant scattering effect on electrons.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] The breakthrough is then applying a pressure to the liquid in the sintering process, which creates a transient flow of the Te rich liquid and facilitates the formation of dislocations that greatly reduce the lattice conductivity.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] The ability to selectively decrease the lattice conductivity results in reported zT value of 1.86, which is a significant improvement over the current commercial thermoelectric generators with zT ~ 0.3–0.6.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] These improvements highlight the fact that in addition to the development of novel materials for thermoelectric applications, using different processing techniques to design microstructure is a viable and worthwhile effort.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] In fact, it often makes sense to work to optimize both composition and microstructure.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Thermoelectric generators (TEG) have a variety of applications.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Frequently, thermoelectric generators are used for low power remote applications or where bulkier but more efficient heat engines such as Stirling engines would not be possible.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Unlike heat engines, the solid state electrical components typically used to perform thermal to electric energy conversion have no moving parts.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] The thermal to electric energy conversion can be performed using components that require no maintenance, have inherently high reliability, and can be used to construct generators with long service-free lifetimes.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] This makes thermoelectric generators well suited for equipment with low to modest power needs in remote uninhabited or inaccessible locations such as mountaintops, the vacuum of space, or the deep ocean.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Solar cells use only the high-frequency part of the radiation, while the low-frequency heat energy is wasted.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Several patents about the use of thermoelectric devices in parallel or cascade configuration with solar cells have been filed.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] The idea is to increase the efficiency of the combined solar/thermoelectric system to convert solar radiation into useful electricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Conventional solar cells also suffer from decreased efficiency (-0.45%/°C) as temperature increases, and the inclusion of TEGs could help dissipate this waste heat while simultaneously increasing solar panel efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] There are two potential methods for coupling TEGs to photovoltaic panels.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Mechanically, the simplest is a thermally coupled system.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] This involves mounting TEGs in an array behind the PV panel.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Heat flows from the panel's rear surface into the hot side of the TE modules, which must be cooled on the other side.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] A simple approach to generate the necessary temperature gradient across the TEGs is to apply heat sinks to promote convective cooling.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] The second system is to optically couple photovoltaic cells with TEGs.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Using mirrors and filters, incoming solar irradiance is split into two bands.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] The higher-wavelength infrared spectrum is diverted to an array of TEGs where the thermal energy is scavenged for electricity generation.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] All other wavelengths are sent to the photovoltaic panel where it is converted to electricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Under ambient conditions, with thermally coupled systems, efficiencies of 3.05% were reported.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Higher gains have been noted under optimized conditions.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] One research group placed a PV-TEG system in an evacuated chamber to prevent convection on the top (hot) surface of the PV array, and to allow them to more carefully control the temperature gradient across the TEGs.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] They reported an efficiency increase of the TEGs from previously reported values of 0.5% up to 4.4%.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Another method for regulating the temperature gradient across TEGs is the use of phase-change materials (PCMs).
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] These materials can help maintain a constant cold-side temperature over the entire panel area and avoid hot spots that may reduce PV efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] They also maintain the cold-side of the TEGs at a fixed temperature, and can help smooth out power generation and thus efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Organic-metal hybrid PCMs use nontoxic materials like coconut oil or beeswax coupled with metallic nanoparticles to facilitate thermal conduction into the material for efficient heat transfer.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] All of the practical limitations to implementation discussed above apply to these PV-TEG systems.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Until TEGs can produce higher than single-digit efficiencies under typical temperature gradients in ambient conditions, they will remain on the fringe of commercial development.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] The added cost of including TEG arrays on solar panels cannot be justified for the marginal efficiency gains seen with current materials and architectures.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] The Institute of Optics has announced a Solar Thermoelectric Generator (STEG) capable of efficiencies claimed to be up to 15%.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] While TEG technology has been used in military and aerospace applications for decades, new TE materials and systems are being developed to generate power using low or high temperatures waste heat, and that could provide a significant opportunity in the near future.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] These systems can also be scalable to any size and have lower operation and maintenance cost.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] The global market for thermoelectric generators is estimated to be US$320 million in 2015 and US$472 million in 2021; up to US$1.44 billion by 2030 with a CAGR of 11.8%.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Today, North America captures 66% of the market share and it will continue to be the biggest market in the near future.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] However, Asia-Pacific and European countries are projected to grow at relatively higher rates.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Small scale thermoelectric generators are also in the early stages of investigation in wearable technologies to reduce or replace charging and boost charge duration.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Recent studies focused on the novel development of a flexible inorganic thermoelectric, silver selenide, on a nylon substrate.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Thermoelectrics represent particular synergy with wearables by harvesting energy directly from the human body creating a self-powered device.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] One project used n-type silver selenide on a nylon membrane.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Silver selenide is a narrow bandgap semiconductor with high electrical conductivity and low thermal conductivity, making it perfect for thermoelectric applications.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Low power TEG or "sub-watt" (i.e. generating up to 1 watt peak) market is a growing part of the TEG market, capitalizing on the latest technologies.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] Main applications are sensors, low power applications and more globally Internet of things applications.
[src:energy-harvesting-circuits/thermoelectric-generator] A specialized market research company indicated that 100,000 units have been shipped in 2014 and expects 9 million units per year by 2020.
